	<h1>About</h1>

	<p>
		Letters from the Floor is a publication about the human texture of business — the
		conversations, encounters, and forms of memory that turn strangers into colleagues, customers,
		and friends.
	</p>

	<p>
		We cover the parts of professional life that don't show up in the metrics dashboard: the trade
		show floor at the end of a long day; the lunch that becomes a five-year partnership; the trick
		a veteran salesperson uses to remember the name of every spouse and child of every account she
		works with. We are interested in commerce as a fundamentally human practice — older than
		capitalism, older than the corporation, as old as the first market.
	</p>

	<p>We publish weekly. We are independent.</p>

	<h2>Founder &amp; Editor</h2>

	<p>
		Letters from the Floor is written and edited by Ethan Reese, a writer and entrepreneur based in
		Boston. Ethan is the founder of Overclock Systems, a software company in the field of sales
		technology.
		<strong
			>This publication does not cover sales technology, conversation intelligence software, or any
			product category in which Overclock competes or could plausibly compete in the foreseeable
			future.</strong
		>
		Coverage decisions and editorial judgment are independent of any commercial interest. See our
		<a href="/editorial-standards">Editorial Standards</a> and
		<a href="/disclosure">Disclosure Policy</a> for details.
	</p>

